WEBVTT

01:31.467 --> 01:33.009
Sit up straight.

01:34.636 --> 01:37.430
Heels down. Lighten your hands.

01:39.600 --> 01:41.309
Good girl.

01:44.021 --> 01:45.938
There we go.

01:48.025 --> 01:50.359
Now, if you can step over here.

01:58.160 --> 01:59.535
You're a big one.

01:59.620 --> 02:00.953
Thank you, Lilly.

02:02.623 --> 02:04.290
Have a seat.

02:05.709 --> 02:07.502
So, Mr. Draper,

02:07.586 --> 02:11.088
you haven't had a physical
in quite some time.

02:11.173 --> 02:12.507
I eat a lot of apples.

02:13.926 --> 02:16.093
What is it with you boys?

02:16.178 --> 02:19.180
Why does it take an insurance physical
to get you in here?

02:32.444 --> 02:33.569
What's the number?

02:34.905 --> 02:37.240
Because that will
mean something to you?

02:37.324 --> 02:38.950
It's 1 60 over 1 00,

02:39.034 --> 02:40.618
which is high for boys our age.

02:40.702 --> 02:42.620
Tell me about your parents.

02:42.704 --> 02:44.288
Living or deceased?

02:44.373 --> 02:45.790
Dead. Both.

02:45.874 --> 02:46.958
Ages?

02:47.042 --> 02:48.960
My dad was 41 , 42.

02:49.044 --> 02:50.461
He died in an accident,

02:50.546 --> 02:52.588
and my mother died in childbirth.

02:52.673 --> 02:54.382
She was 22, I think.

02:54.466 --> 02:56.634
How many drinks do you have a day?

02:56.718 --> 02:58.553
Wine, cocktails, beer.

02:58.637 --> 03:01.806
Everything depends on the day.

03:01.890 --> 03:04.392
Days of plenty being?

03:04.476 --> 03:06.018
Three.

03:06.103 --> 03:08.980
You're a high-powered businessman
with a high-tension job.

03:09.064 --> 03:11.065
I'm trying to help you here.

03:11.191 --> 03:12.191
Five.

03:12.276 --> 03:14.151
And two packs a day,
but you're cutting down.

03:14.236 --> 03:15.653
Yes.

03:15.737 --> 03:17.029
All right.

03:17.114 --> 03:19.532
Any changes in the last year?

03:19.616 --> 03:20.658
What do you mean?

03:20.742 --> 03:21.868
In your health.

03:21.952 --> 03:24.495
How do you feel when
you wake up in the morning?

03:24.580 --> 03:25.663
How do you feel?

03:25.747 --> 03:27.415
You live too hard,

03:27.499 --> 03:28.791
and not just at the office.

03:28.876 --> 03:31.544
It'll hit you all at once.

03:34.131 --> 03:38.384
Nope. No, I've been-- I've been good.

03:38.468 --> 03:42.889
All right, I'm going to write you
some reserpine to bring that down

03:42.973 --> 03:46.434
and some phenobarbital to help you relax.

03:46.518 --> 03:48.561
You're 36 years old.

03:48.645 --> 03:51.689
You need to take this seriously.

03:51.773 --> 03:54.025
Buy a boat.

03:54.109 --> 03:55.693
Breathe in.

03:58.155 --> 04:00.197
So I wait for Becky to go play,

04:00.282 --> 04:01.866
and I look in her pencil case.

04:01.950 --> 04:03.701
There's almost 20 dimes.

04:03.785 --> 04:05.536
She stopped eating lunch.

04:05.621 --> 04:07.747
I hate the dishonesty.

04:07.831 --> 04:09.790
You should be glad
she watches what she eats.

04:09.875 --> 04:11.959
That's the truth. She is slimming down.

04:12.044 --> 04:13.502
Good morning, ladies.

04:14.796 --> 04:16.964
You want to get off right here?

04:17.049 --> 04:18.633
You can go right to your car.

04:18.717 --> 04:20.885
No.

04:24.181 --> 04:26.098
He's a prisoner of war.

04:26.183 --> 04:28.142
Because he can't ride.

04:28.268 --> 04:30.394
A man that age doesn't
suddenly take this up.

04:30.479 --> 04:32.355
He's 25.

04:32.439 --> 04:33.814
Did he tell you that?

04:33.899 --> 04:35.566
I think so.

04:35.651 --> 04:37.944
He talks to me. He's engaged.

04:38.028 --> 04:40.696
There's no point in being aloof.

04:40.781 --> 04:43.366
I wouldn't know what to talk about.

04:43.450 --> 04:46.410
Aren't you funny? Are you scandalized?

04:46.495 --> 04:48.537
No.

04:48.622 --> 04:50.957
Well, if you must know,
we talk about you

04:51.041 --> 04:53.292
and how Gertie has a crush on you.

04:53.377 --> 04:55.336
She's a sadist.

04:55.420 --> 04:57.004
I'll see you Saturday.

04:59.007 --> 05:00.967
Don't you hate getting manure in that?

05:01.051 --> 05:04.136
Little children. What's the difference?

05:14.231 --> 05:17.858
Look, miss,
just tell me where you want it.

05:17.943 --> 05:20.611
I could take out the lockers
and use that wall.

05:20.696 --> 05:21.862
The break room?

05:21.947 --> 05:23.197
Don't take away the break room.

05:23.323 --> 05:25.282
I'm not taking away anything.

05:25.367 --> 05:27.618
Believe me, this machine
is a gift to you girls.

05:27.703 --> 05:30.121
Happy Valentine's, girls.

05:30.205 --> 05:32.123
How are you going to wear
that around your neck?

05:32.207 --> 05:33.958
It's much bigger than they said it was.

05:34.042 --> 05:35.292
I think it needs an office.

05:35.377 --> 05:36.836
Come on.

05:36.920 --> 05:39.463
We're already doubling up.
Don't do that.

05:39.548 --> 05:41.507
My roommate works at Ernst & Ernst.

05:41.591 --> 05:43.801
She did her birthday party
invitations on this.

05:43.885 --> 05:45.386
On colored paper.

05:45.470 --> 05:48.723
I told you, miss,
I'll try as many places as you want.

05:50.559 --> 05:53.227
Maybe we should leave it
here for the time being.

06:06.575 --> 06:08.284
I don't care. I'm doing this.

06:08.368 --> 06:12.830
If you think that if you start eating,
we're all going to join you, you're wrong.

06:12.914 --> 06:15.791
Look, Don's not one
to stand on ceremony.

06:15.876 --> 06:17.710
He's not going to care.

06:17.794 --> 06:20.337
I made it. I knew Draper would be late.

06:20.422 --> 06:21.922
I have some crackers in my desk.

06:23.383 --> 06:24.925
So, burning the midnight oil.

06:25.010 --> 06:26.677
S'all right.

06:26.762 --> 06:28.179
Hope the words are good

06:28.263 --> 06:29.472
'cause he ain't got any artwork.

06:29.556 --> 06:31.348
You didn't have time to giνe it to Art?

06:31.433 --> 06:34.018
You want to start living here?

06:34.102 --> 06:37.605
I'm supposed to be at The Pen and Pencil
by 1 2:30 every day.

06:37.689 --> 06:38.856
I was promised.

06:38.940 --> 06:40.858
Look, Freddie, the eating is the thing.

06:40.942 --> 06:42.318
I'm sure you can have a drink.

06:42.402 --> 06:44.236
It's an unspoken agreement.

06:44.321 --> 06:46.280
I got you, Freddie.

06:48.408 --> 06:50.034
Are these all the glasses, Peggy?

06:51.161 --> 06:52.369
I don't know.

06:52.454 --> 06:54.121
We have artwork.

06:56.875 --> 07:00.002
Peggy, go see if we can expect Don today.

07:05.467 --> 07:06.967
That's a good idea.

07:07.052 --> 07:09.637
Draper's not going to yell at her.

07:09.721 --> 07:11.847
You want to be alone with that?

07:11.932 --> 07:13.766
I'm telling you, Draper knocked her up.

07:13.850 --> 07:15.392
She goes away for a couple of months,

07:15.477 --> 07:17.144
drops about 9 pounds, 8 ounces,

07:17.229 --> 07:18.604
comes back with a job.

07:18.688 --> 07:20.940
Don's been screwing me
for the last three years.

07:21.024 --> 07:22.149
I've got nothing.

07:24.444 --> 07:25.820
What's everybody laughing at?

07:25.904 --> 07:29.573
The great debate wages on
about Peggy Olson's charmed career.

07:29.658 --> 07:31.575
Fat farm.

07:31.660 --> 07:33.452
I thought we had νerification.

07:35.872 --> 07:38.249
Do you have any idea when
you'll be expecting Mr. Draper?

07:38.333 --> 07:41.127
I was expecting him
at the beginning of work today,

07:41.211 --> 07:43.838
but then he called and said he'd be late.

07:43.922 --> 07:46.006
He said he was going to the movies.

07:46.091 --> 07:47.675
Pinocchio.

07:48.677 --> 07:50.511
Thank you.

07:55.851 --> 07:58.269
Are you insinuating something?

07:59.521 --> 08:02.439
I wasn't doing anything, I don't think.

08:02.524 --> 08:04.984
Well, I believe that.

08:05.068 --> 08:06.402
I want you to imagine,

08:06.486 --> 08:07.653
when you talk about Mr. Draper,

08:07.737 --> 08:09.989
that he's standing right behind you.

08:10.073 --> 08:11.949
And think about that
whenever you speak of him.

08:12.033 --> 08:14.743
Are you going to tell on me?

08:14.828 --> 08:16.954
I didn't know. What did I do?

08:17.038 --> 08:18.581
Do you know where Mr. Draper is?

08:18.665 --> 08:20.166
No, l don't.

08:20.250 --> 08:22.418
I think he was joking.

08:22.502 --> 08:26.964
Lois, do you know where Mr. Draper is?

08:29.551 --> 08:31.302
He's out.

08:31.386 --> 08:33.804
Thank you, Lois.

08:59.080 --> 09:01.081
How is it?

09:02.542 --> 09:03.959
He wrote some of it here.

09:04.044 --> 09:08.505
Some of it on 23rd Street,
some place they tore down.

09:08.590 --> 09:11.675
Makes you feel better
about sitting in a bar at lunch.

09:11.760 --> 09:14.094
Makes you feel like you're
getting something done.

09:14.179 --> 09:17.431
Yeah. It's all about getting things done.

09:19.935 --> 09:22.186
Is it good?

09:22.270 --> 09:25.064
I don't think you'd like it.

09:31.988 --> 09:33.739
You wanted to see me?

09:33.823 --> 09:36.825
I wanted to see that Valentine heart.

09:36.910 --> 09:39.119
On my way out. Anything else?

09:39.204 --> 09:42.081
I'm taking Mona to Lutèce.

09:42.165 --> 09:43.958
Let me hear what the living are up to.

09:44.042 --> 09:45.209
You love her.

09:45.293 --> 09:47.378
What happened to the Jewish doctor?

09:47.462 --> 09:48.712
He's not Jewish.

09:48.797 --> 09:50.130
Not anymore, but he was. Trust me.

09:50.215 --> 09:51.298
Is he still a doctor?

09:51.383 --> 09:52.925
You sound like a little girl.

09:53.009 --> 09:54.176
What do you care?

09:55.220 --> 09:57.638
I wish you every happiness.

09:57.722 --> 10:00.724
I'm well aware this is vicarious.
I already said that.

10:00.809 --> 10:02.977
I already know what day
he's going to ask me.

10:03.061 --> 10:04.478
Does he know that?

10:04.604 --> 10:07.898
Because I have a feeling
there's a penalty for passing that date.

10:07.983 --> 10:10.859
He knows.

10:12.320 --> 10:14.947
Mr. Phillips here to see you.

10:15.031 --> 10:16.198
Send him in.

10:18.201 --> 10:19.952
Joan.

10:20.036 --> 10:21.412
Did you girls get my candy?

10:21.496 --> 10:24.498
Yes. It was appreciated
and yet unappreciated.

10:24.624 --> 10:26.417
Anything else?

10:26.501 --> 10:29.420
No, thank you. That'll be all.

10:29.504 --> 10:31.380
Got a second?

10:34.175 --> 10:36.427
Nothing good ever started
with that sentence.

10:36.511 --> 10:39.013
It's not that. It's Martinson's Coffee.

10:39.097 --> 10:41.682
I'm excited about the possibility
of that happening,

10:41.766 --> 10:43.058
and, as you recall,

10:43.143 --> 10:44.768
Martinson's Coffee has a unique problem.

10:44.853 --> 10:47.104
Good. We like that.

10:47.188 --> 10:48.605
Well, that's just it.

10:48.690 --> 10:50.899
No one under 25 drinks coffee anymore.

10:50.984 --> 10:52.318
Just Pepsi.

10:52.402 --> 10:53.819
They pour it on their Frosted Flakes.

10:53.903 --> 10:56.322
For those who think young.

10:56.406 --> 10:57.948
Which is why I was
disappointed to see Don

10:58.033 --> 10:59.450
put Fred Rumsen on this.

10:59.534 --> 11:01.160
So Freddie doesn't drink coffee.

11:01.244 --> 11:02.661
He doesn't wear a bra, either.

11:02.746 --> 11:04.538
He managed to do a good job on Playtex.

11:04.664 --> 11:06.874
It's frustrating not to haνe
young people around here.

11:06.958 --> 11:08.125
We're a young country.

11:08.209 --> 11:09.293
The president has a baby.

11:09.377 --> 11:10.627
Have you been out there?

11:10.712 --> 11:12.588
It's rotten with kids.

11:12.672 --> 11:14.506
And the cologne they wear.

11:14.591 --> 11:16.717
Real kids. 25. Even less.

11:16.801 --> 11:17.968
Maybe one of those teams.

11:18.053 --> 11:19.762
The writer and the artist together.

11:19.846 --> 11:21.430
Clients keep bringing it up.

11:21.514 --> 11:24.016
Talk to Don about it.
Just for Martinson's Coffee alone.

11:24.100 --> 11:26.477
Can't you talk to Don about it?

11:26.561 --> 11:28.479
I thought this was the way
things were done here.

11:28.563 --> 11:30.773
Didn't you tell me you were a bridge
between Accounts and Don?

11:30.857 --> 11:33.484
Doesn't sound like me.

11:33.568 --> 11:35.361
Look, Don has talent.

11:35.445 --> 11:37.404
You know how to deal
with that, don't you?

11:37.489 --> 11:38.572
Just assume that he knows

11:38.698 --> 11:40.407
as much about business as you do,

11:40.492 --> 11:43.577
but inside there's a child
who likes getting his way.

11:43.703 --> 11:45.871
He's not my first creatiνe director.

11:45.955 --> 11:48.749
This is about a sales reality
and not personal territory.

11:48.833 --> 11:52.294
It's what the clients are asking for,
and we need to have it.

11:52.379 --> 11:55.381
What's the best way to make it happen?

11:59.052 --> 12:00.260
Mr. Draper.

12:00.345 --> 12:01.512
Any calls?

12:01.596 --> 12:03.013
Yes, and there was your 1 2:00

12:03.098 --> 12:04.807
in the conference room.

12:07.435 --> 12:09.770
Of course.

12:16.778 --> 12:19.238
Well, girls can say whatever they want.

12:19.322 --> 12:20.531
They want the chocolates.

12:20.615 --> 12:22.408
Right, Peggy?

12:22.492 --> 12:23.909
Of course they do.

12:23.993 --> 12:26.912
I don't do anything.
Keeps them off balance.

12:26.996 --> 12:28.664
Hey, chief.

12:30.625 --> 12:31.834
Sorry we're late.

12:31.918 --> 12:35.712
I think the little ones need to eat.

12:35.797 --> 12:37.881
What do we haνe? Dale, wake up.

12:37.966 --> 12:39.800
I could just go.

12:39.884 --> 12:41.427
Or Kinsey.

12:41.511 --> 12:43.011
You want to go first?

12:44.472 --> 12:45.597
Peggy.

12:45.682 --> 12:48.308
I just wrote copy for Dale.

12:52.313 --> 12:56.567
Well, this is kind of the gist,
because I was--

12:56.651 --> 12:58.569
Well, we were--

12:58.653 --> 12:59.987
It just kept changing course.

13:02.240 --> 13:05.784
"Mohawk Airlines.
There's a new chief in the sky."

13:05.869 --> 13:08.662
And I thought, following that,

13:08.788 --> 13:10.664
"Most routes to Boston.

13:10.790 --> 13:12.791
Circle the wagons,
we've got it surrounded."

13:12.876 --> 13:16.503
And there'd be wagons
around a dot that says "Boston."

13:16.588 --> 13:18.464
I can almost picture it. Sal.

13:18.548 --> 13:20.340
This is the first time
l'm hearing it, too.

13:20.425 --> 13:23.260
So it's about an airline
that's flown by Indians?

13:23.344 --> 13:26.305
Maybe a plane with some arrows
stuck in the cargo door?

13:26.389 --> 13:27.598
That's funny.

13:27.682 --> 13:30.476
That's what gets people's
attention now, right?

13:30.560 --> 13:31.768
There has to be advertising

13:31.853 --> 13:33.645
for people who don't
have a sense of humor.

13:33.730 --> 13:34.938
I understand, Don.

13:35.023 --> 13:36.690
What else you got?

13:36.816 --> 13:38.942
Seνeral more Indian puns.

13:39.027 --> 13:41.528
Stop writing for other writers.

13:45.950 --> 13:48.410
Luxury, service.

13:48.495 --> 13:50.704
A lot of people are afraid of turbulence,

13:50.830 --> 13:52.331
so it's dead calm.

13:52.415 --> 13:54.875
Look how level those drinks are.

13:54.959 --> 13:56.793
"Wherever Mohawk takes us."

13:56.878 --> 13:58.378
Or, "You'll love getting there."

13:58.463 --> 13:59.671
What's outside that window?

13:59.756 --> 14:01.840
- Fluffy clouds.
- Research.

14:01.925 --> 14:04.593
I get on a plane,
I don't care where I'm going.

14:04.677 --> 14:07.179
I just want to see the city
disappearing behind me.

14:07.263 --> 14:10.140
So we could take the clouds
out of there and put in the city.

14:10.225 --> 14:11.558
The Chrysler Building.

14:12.602 --> 14:14.603
That Indian...

14:16.064 --> 14:20.442
It's not about the majestic beauty
of the Mohawk Nation.

14:23.863 --> 14:26.823
It's about adventure.

14:26.908 --> 14:29.826
Could be a pirate.

14:29.911 --> 14:31.411
Could be a knight in shining armor.

14:31.496 --> 14:35.749
Could be a conquistador
getting off of a boat.

14:37.335 --> 14:39.127
It's about a fantastical people

14:39.212 --> 14:42.923
who are taking you someplace
where you've never been.

14:51.975 --> 14:54.726
We could dress the stew
as Pocahontas.

14:54.811 --> 14:56.228
With the cheekbones.

14:56.312 --> 14:57.980
How's his wife going to feel about that?

14:58.064 --> 15:01.108
Air travel's too expensive
to waste on your wife.

15:01.192 --> 15:02.901
You want to get
on a plane to feel aliνe.

15:02.986 --> 15:06.196
You want to get on a plane
to see just the hint of a woman's thigh

15:06.281 --> 15:09.658
because her skirt
is just this much too short.

15:10.785 --> 15:12.160
Friday?

15:12.245 --> 15:14.413
Tomorrow.

15:16.374 --> 15:18.208
What does that mean?

15:18.293 --> 15:21.211
It means you want to go somewhere,
go up her skirt.

15:21.296 --> 15:23.463
That's the impression l got.

15:26.593 --> 15:29.303
Carla, Bobby's turning blue out there.

15:31.097 --> 15:33.098
Did somebody get a lot of valentines?

15:33.182 --> 15:36.310
They made everybody
give one to everybody else.

15:36.394 --> 15:38.186
That defeats the purpose.

15:38.271 --> 15:39.563
They had a party.

15:39.647 --> 15:42.024
I see. Fruit punch?

15:42.108 --> 15:43.650
I'm making this for Daddy.

15:43.735 --> 15:44.901
It's beautiful.

15:44.986 --> 15:47.029
I'll see that he gets it.

15:47.113 --> 15:49.114
Mommy, can l do it?

15:49.198 --> 15:50.657
Okay.

15:54.704 --> 15:56.622
I want to go riding with you.

15:56.706 --> 15:58.749
- You can't.
- Well, why?

15:58.833 --> 16:00.917
Well, for one thing, it's too dangerous.

16:01.002 --> 16:02.544
No, it's not.

16:02.629 --> 16:06.381
Do you remember what happened
to the little girl in Gone With the Wind?

16:08.009 --> 16:09.718
You are taking a bath tonight.

16:18.686 --> 16:21.938
They say once you start drinking alone,
you're an alcoholic.

16:22.023 --> 16:24.024
I'm really trying to avoid that.

16:24.108 --> 16:26.026
So I guess l'm helping both of us.

16:26.110 --> 16:28.779
Cooper wants younger people.

16:28.863 --> 16:30.030
For what purpose?

16:30.114 --> 16:31.531
Martinson's Coffee.

16:31.616 --> 16:34.117
Last time Freddie Rumsen
had a cup of coffee,

16:34.202 --> 16:37.329
it was one of five being poured
down his throat by a cop.

16:38.998 --> 16:42.626
Well, young campaigns don't necessarily
come from young people.

16:42.710 --> 16:43.877
The clients like it.

16:44.003 --> 16:47.798
The clients like the thrill of young talent.

16:47.882 --> 16:49.591
So what am I supposed to do?

16:49.676 --> 16:50.842
Dangle a Pepsi out the window

16:50.927 --> 16:52.803
and see if I can hook a stroller?

16:52.887 --> 16:54.763
I have some candidates.

16:56.057 --> 16:57.349
This smells like Accounts to me.

16:57.433 --> 16:59.434
I had Paul Kinsey make up a list.

16:59.519 --> 17:01.812
He had no idea he was signing
his own death warrant.

17:03.022 --> 17:04.356
You want younger people than that?

17:04.440 --> 17:06.692
What do you want me to say?

17:06.776 --> 17:11.488
Tell Duck clients don't understand.

17:11.572 --> 17:16.660
Their success is related to standing out,
not fitting in.

17:16.744 --> 17:18.829
It's a fad.

17:18.913 --> 17:20.247
Paint him a picture.

17:20.331 --> 17:24.835
Something like one wants to be
the needle in the haystack,

17:24.919 --> 17:26.712
not a haystack.

17:26.796 --> 17:29.631
Donald, isn't it possible
that the recently weaned

17:29.716 --> 17:32.426
have some unique perspectiνe?

17:32.510 --> 17:34.511
Joy, enthusiasm.

17:34.595 --> 17:37.139
You're talking as if they're
some fresh version of us.

